# a11y — opt-in (default: absent → a11y audit does NOT run; web-only)
# Story 19.4; FR-P2-6 | ADR-011
# How to enable: uncomment the block below on a `project_type: web` project to
# run the axe-core accessibility audit per AC. axe-core (Deque, MPL-2.0,
# version_floor 4.12) is injected in-page via the EXISTING Playwright MCP browser
# surface (`axe.min.js` + `axe.run()`) — NO new MCP server. The audit runs ONLY
# when BOTH gates hold: `project_type == web` AND `a11y.enabled: true`. On
# `project_type: api|mobile`, on `a11y.enabled: false`, and on the unconfigured
# default (this block absent), the audit is a SILENT skip — NO `a11y-*` marker
# fires (the opt-in-skip / default-defer posture of FR-P2-6 + ADR-011, mirroring
# `masked_selectors` / `heuristics` above; emitting a marker on inapplicable
# project-type or not-enabled would be the exact noise FR42 / ADR-010 warn
# against). axe-core ships NO native baseline-delta (the load-bearing ADR-011
# finding); the Automator self-computes the delta over the `violations[]` JSON
# (set-difference of `(rule-id, target-selector)` keys) against a per-AC baseline.
# ABSENCE of this block is NOT a marker (FR42 user-owned file — absence means
# "a11y audit deferred").
# Baseline storage: per-AC baselines live under
# `_bmad-output/qa-a11y-baseline/{story-id}/{ac-id}/baseline.json` (gitignored —
# practitioner-local longitudinal signal, the qa-evidence precedent). To
# re-anchor a baseline, delete the stored `baseline.json`; the next run creates a
# fresh anchor and emits the informational `a11y-baseline-stale` marker.
# See `docs/a11y-setup.md` for the full operator walkthrough.
# Worked example (uncomment to enable on a web project):
# a11y:
#   enabled: true
#   # delta_threshold — the count of NEWLY-introduced violation keys (beyond the
#   # baseline) tolerated before `a11y-delta-exceeded` fires. Default 0 = "any new
#   # violation is a regression" (the strictest, most defensible opt-in default).
#   delta_threshold: 0
#   # scope — `per-ac` (default): one `axe.run()` per AC against that AC's
#   # verified surface, one baseline per (story, ac). `per-story` collapses to a
#   # single whole-story audit + baseline. Omit for the per-AC default.
#   scope: per-ac
# ---

# ---
# visual_regression — opt-in (default: absent → audit does NOT run; web-AND-mobile)
# Story 19.5; FR-P2-10 | ADR-012
# How to enable: uncomment the block below on a `project_type: web` OR
# `project_type: mobile` project to run the pixelmatch visual-regression audit
# per AC. pixelmatch (Mapbox, ISC, version_floor 7.2 — the engine Playwright's
# `toHaveScreenshot` uses internally) + its `pngjs` decode companion install via
# `npm install pixelmatch pngjs`. Screenshots are captured via the EXISTING
# Playwright MCP `browser_take_screenshot` (web) / mobile-mcp
# `mobile_take_screenshot` (mobile) surfaces; the pixelmatch diff runs over the
# saved PNGs — NO new MCP server. The audit runs ONLY when BOTH gates hold:
# `project_type ∈ {web, mobile}` AND `visual_regression.enabled: true`. On
# `project_type: api` (no UI to capture), on `visual_regression.enabled: false`,
# and on the unconfigured default (this block absent), the audit is a SILENT skip
# — NO `visual-regression-*` marker fires (the opt-in-skip / default-defer posture
# of FR-P2-10 + ADR-012, mirroring `masked_selectors` / `heuristics` / `a11y`
# above; emitting a marker on an inapplicable project-type or a not-enabled audit
# is the exact noise FR42 warns against). pixelmatch ships NO baseline lifecycle
# (the load-bearing ADR-012 finding); the Automator self-computes the
# mismatched-pixel RATIO (`mismatched_pixels / total_pixels`) against a per-AC
# baseline. ABSENCE of this block is NOT a marker (FR42 user-owned file — absence
# means "visual-regression audit deferred").
# Baseline storage: per-AC baselines live under
# `_bmad-output/qa-visual-baseline/{story-id}/{ac-id}/baseline.png`. GITIGNORED by
# default (practitioner-local longitudinal signal, the qa-evidence precedent); set
# `baseline_storage: committed` to curate baselines in-repo (visual baselines are
# images a team may legitimately want to commit, unlike a11y's JSON key set). To
# re-anchor a baseline, DELETE the stored `baseline.png` (manual-delete only —
# there is NO `force_reanchor` field); the next run creates a fresh anchor and
# emits the informational `visual-regression-baseline-missing` marker.
# See `docs/visual-regression-setup.md` for the full operator walkthrough.
# Worked example (uncomment to enable on a web or mobile project):
# visual_regression:
#   enabled: true
#   # delta_threshold — the mismatched-pixel RATIO (0.0–1.0) tolerated before
#   # `visual-regression-delta-exceeded` fires. Default 0 = "any pixel difference
#   # beyond pixelmatch's anti-aliasing + color tolerance is a regression" (the
#   # strictest, most defensible opt-in default).
#   delta_threshold: 0
#   # scope — `per-ac` (default): one screenshot + baseline per AC against that
#   # AC's verified surface. `per-story` collapses to a single whole-story
#   # snapshot + baseline. Omit for the per-AC default.
#   scope: per-ac
#   # baseline_storage — `gitignored` (default; the qa-evidence precedent —
#   # practitioner-local, not committed history) OR `committed` (maintainer-
#   # curated in-repo baselines). Omit for the gitignored default.
#   baseline_storage: gitignored
# ---

